{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17502412","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17502412"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:43:35+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:43:35+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1855"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1855","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1855"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.2,0.18,0.4,0.05,0.17]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1855"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107465"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1855","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1855"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1855"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89945"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"678"},{"type":"tags","id":"1139"},{"type":"tags","id":"1293"},{"type":"tags","id":"1449"},{"type":"tags","id":"3696"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"},{"type":"tags","id":"5771"},{"type":"tags","id":"9098"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1109"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17614"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39344"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107465","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/107465"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 73-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a 12-hour history of rapid-onset and steadily increasing left iliac fossa pain. This is associated with bloody diarrhoea. She has never had these symptoms before. Two days earlier, she was started on a course of amoxicillin/clavulanic acid for a presumed urinary tract infection. She has a medical history of atrial fibrillation and hypertension, for which she takes apixaban and amlodipine. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears unwell. Her pulse rate is 100/min and irregular, blood pressure 140/90 mmHg, respiratory rate 20/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.4\u00b0C. Her abdomen is soft but tender in the left iliac fossa. Rectal examination reveals soft stool mixed with fresh blood.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next investigation to establish the diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Stool microscopy and culture","Colonoscopy with biopsy","CT abdomen","Serum lactate","Angiography"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient\u0027s presentation is highly suggestive of ischaemic colitis, given her age, acute onset of left-sided abdominal pain, and bloody diarrhoea. The irregular pulse also suggests atrial fibrillation, which is a risk factor for ischaemic colitis due to potential embolism.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECT abdomen\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate initial investigation for suspected ischaemic colitis. It can be performed quickly and provides valuable information about the extent and severity of the condition. CT can identify colonic wall thickening, mesenteric stranding, and pneumatosis, which are characteristic findings in ischaemic colitis. Additionally, CT angiography can evaluate the patency of mesenteric vessels.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EColonoscopy with biopsy\u003C/strong\u003E is an important diagnostic tool for ischaemic colitis, but it is typically performed within 48 hours of presentation if CT findings are inconclusive. Colonoscopy can visualise the affected mucosa and allow for biopsy, which can show ischaemic changes. However, it is more invasive than CT and may not be immediately available in an emergency setting.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStool microscopy and culture\u003C/strong\u003E would be more appropriate if infectious colitis was the primary concern. While it may be ordered as part of the workup, it is not the most useful test for diagnosing ischaemic colitis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESerum lactate\u003C/strong\u003E can be elevated in ischaemic colitis, particularly in severe cases. However, it is not specific to ischaemic colitis and can be elevated in various conditions involving tissue hypoperfusion. While it may be part of the initial blood work, it is not the most appropriate test to establish the diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAngiography\u003C/strong\u003E can be both diagnostic and therapeutic in ischaemic colitis, particularly if there is evidence of a widespread ischaemic process. However, it is usually performed after CT or CT angiography has suggested a vascular occlusion amenable to intervention. It is more invasive than CT and is not typically the first-line investigation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn summary, CT abdomen is the most appropriate initial investigation for suspected ischaemic colitis. It provides rapid, non-invasive assessment of the bowel wall and mesenteric vessels, guiding further management decisions. If CT is inconclusive, colonoscopy with biopsy would typically be the next step in establishing the diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Acute abdominal pain and bloody diarrhoea in an older patient should be considered due to ischaemic colitis until proven otherwise.","CT abdomen is the most appropriate initial investigation for suspected ischaemic colitis, as it can identify colonic wall thickening, mesenteric stranding, and pneumatosis.","Colonoscopy with biopsy is typically performed within 48 hours if CT findings are inconclusive for ischaemic colitis."],"references":["Trotter JM, Hunt L, Peter MB. Ischaemic colitis. BMJ 2016;355:6600. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/28007701/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89945"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1855"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89945","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/89945"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-30T08:28:51+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-30T08:30:22+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1855"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107465"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"65","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tag